-- BHP, Rio, APN, GPT Group, iSOFT, Rio, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-07T22:44:57Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-07/bhp-rio-apn-gpt-group-isoft-rio-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed yesterday. All
prices are from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
climbed 2 percent to 4,332 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 3.4 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  lost 0.5 percent to 4,254.60.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September climbed 1.5
percent to $3.015 a pound in New York.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
rose 0.8 percent to A$37.43 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts climbed 3.4 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto
Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining company, gained
1.1 percent to A$65.84 in Sydney.  
 Aluminum Corp. of China, that nation’s biggest producer of
the metal, is in talks with Rio to buy a stake in the $4.6
billion Oyu Tolgoi mine in Mongolia or the U.K. company’s
partner in the project, Ivanhoe Mines Ltd.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil rose for the first time in seven
days in New York following a forecast that U.S. retail sales are
growing at the fastest pace in four years.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, fell 0.8 percent to A$41.30. Rival
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) dropped 0.9 percent to A$12.45.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures rose in New York, erasing
losses, on speculation that the lowest prices in six weeks
reflected a sell-off that was overdone.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, dropped 2 percent to A$33.48.  
 APN News & Media Ltd  (APN AU): The publisher of newspapers
in Australia and New Zealand was raised to “buy” from “hold”
at BBY Limited by equity analyst  Mark McDonnell . APN fell 2
percent to A$1.92.  
 GPT Group  (GPT AU): The Australian property trust is the
leading bidder for the Top Ryde City shopping center in Sydney
that may sell for A$700 million, the Australian Financial Review
reported in its Street Talk column, without saying where it got
the information. GPT advanced 0.7 percent to A$2.87.  
 iSOFT Group Ltd.  (ISF AU): The health information software
developer was raised to “hold” from “sell” at Deutsche Bank
AG by equity analyst  Michael Simotas . iSOFT slumped 5.3 percent
to 18 Australian cents.  
 National Australia Bank Ltd.  (NAB AU) and  Axa Asia Pacific
Holdings  (AXA AU): Australia’s competition regulator may not
make a decision on National Australia Bank’s possible renewed
bid for asset manager Axa Asia Pacific until September, the
Australian newspaper reported, without saying where it got the
information. National Australia Bank dropped 1.3 percent to
A$23.09 and Axa Asia shares fell 1.7 percent to A$5.35.  
